question.text: Some bacteria possess an additional mechanism to regulate the production of enzymes involved in the tryptophan (Trp) biosynthesis. The tryptophan (Trp) operon possesses, prior to the actual genes ([i]trpA-E[/i]), a leader sequence ([i]trpL[/i]) coding for a leader peptide. ([i]trpL[/i]) contains two tryptophan codons next to each other.

At high tryptophan concentrations, the ribosome translates the mRNA of the leader peptide and stalls at the stop codon, thereby masking segment 1 of the mRNA and allowing segments 2 and 3 to form a stem loop. A stem loop followed by poly-U is a termination signal for the RNA polymerase (RNA pol), which falls off the DNA.

However, at low tryptophan concentrations, the ribosome gets stalled at the tryptophan codons allowing 1 and 2 to form a stem loop. The whole tryptophan operon can be transcribed by the RNA polymerase.
question.task: Indicate for each of the following statement if it is true or false.

answerlist.choice: The same regulation mechanism also works for nuclear genes in eukaryotes.

With reduced concentration of the aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase that attaches tryptophan to tRNA[sup]Trp[/sup], transcription of the [i]trpA-E[/i] genes will be inactivated at a lower tryptophan concentration.
After deletion of one of the two tryptophan codons in the gene coding for the leader peptide, transcription of the [i]trpA-E[/i] genes will be inactivated at a lower tryptophan concentration.
In case of a mutation destabilizing the stem loop 1-2, transcription of the [i]trpA-E[/i] genes will be inactivated at a lower tryptophan concentration.

question.text: Bacterial count of a liquid culture can be determined by different methods. Cells can be counted under a microscope using a counting chamber, the optical dispersion of the culture can be measured in a spectrophotometer (with OD[sub]600[/sub] = 1 corresponding to 8x10[sup]8[/sup] bacterial cells/ml) or several dilutions of the culture are plated on agar and the colonies are counted (see picture) to calculate the number of colony forming units per milliliter (cfu/ml).
question.task: Indicate for each of the following statements if it is true or false.

answerlist.choice: A culture with OD[sub]600[/sub] = 0.1 and a doubling time of 30 minutes will reach 4x10[sup]8[/sup] cells/ml in less than two hours of growth.
Counting colonies on plates gives a smaller estimate of the number of bacterial cells than counting cells under a microscope.
Using the plate giving the most accurate results, the culture X is estimated to contain 1.6x10[sup]5[/sup] cfu/ml.
When repeating the plating of dilution f many times, some plates will show colonies.

question.text: In a living organism, cells die either through apoptosis (programmed cell death) or necrosis (cells swell and burst).
question.task: Indicate for each statement if it is true or false.

answerlist.choice: Apoptosis is induced in immature T-cells that recognize self antigens.
Apoptosis is induced in intestinal epithelial cells losing contact with the basal lamina.
Neural stem cells undergoing apoptosis expose on their surface a signal promoting phagocytosis.
Necrosis often induces an inflammatory immune response.

question.text: The chorismate pathway leading to the synthesis of aromatic amino acids is presented here.
The velocity of the enzyme chorismate mutase (CM) was assessed in the absence (--) as well as in the presence of either tryptophan (+Trp) or tyrosine (+Tyr).
question.task: Based on these results, indicate for each of the following statements if it is true or false.

answerlist.choice: Tryptophan increases the activity of chorismate mutase.
Tryptophan, but not tyrosine inhibits the synthesis of erythrose-4-P.
A high concentration of tyrosine is likely to increase the synthesis of tryptophan.
The prephenate and the anthranilate branches compete for chorismate.

question.text: The sensitivity of an enzyme for different inhibitors is assessed. The rate of product formation was measured at different concentrations of substrate with 10 nM enzyme. The initial velocity v[sub]i[/sub] (at t = 0 s) was calculated and plotted as a function of the substrate concentration in the absence or presence of two different inhibitors.
question.task: Indicate for each statement if it is true or false.

answerlist.choice: In the absence of any inhibitor, the K[sub]m[/sub] (Michaelis constant) of the enzyme is 0.15 M.
The effect of Inhibitor 1 can be largely compensated by adding more substrate.
Inhibitor 2 reduces the maximal velocity of the enzyme.
The turnover number (maximum number of molecules processed per second by one enzyme molecule) under inhibition by inhibitor 2 is about 15/s.
